{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930103101/1121.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD. FRIDAY,- OCTOBER 31,-1930.\nlonergan Target at G. 0. P. Rally;\nSpeakers Say Tariff Is Necessary\nt-T Protect America's Workingmen\nSeymour Says Factories\ngj Would Close If Demo-\ncrats Won Qiiigley\nCalls Annexation Issue\nZ Middletown Mayor De-\nnies Republicans Are to\nt Blame for Depression.\n2 Nearly i\"\nmembers\n5Jf the John Ericsson\nind frh-:i !:i\nKciiublicMii\nlub gathered in Odd Fellows' hall\n2n Arch street last night to hear :i\nSing list of republican speakers tell\njfchy they thought the members\nIgiould vote the republican ticket\nI1cxt Tuesday, and despite the long\nJrogram, most of the audience stay\n1 to the finish and heard Judge\n4arl F. Anderson of Middletown, in\ng voice of thunder, berate the\n-democratic leaders.\n$i The principal speaker was Mayor\namuel A. Carlson of Jamestown, N.\nt j., who told several stories and gave\nconsiderable praise, to resident\nJioover and his work durinrr the\n.\"ft-isf two years. Mayor George\nfiiji.Tlcy, in a burst of impais ionc I\nready to ship -wheat to Italy, but\nthe tariff there prevents this.' Our\ndemocratic friends say the republi\ncans are to blame for this condition.\nThis fs not so, if it were, then the\nUnited States -would be the only na\ntion to feel any depression. The\nwhole world is affected.\nKnocks 9 Billion Off\n\"The republican party did abig\nthing in the past 10 years. There\nwas a national debt of twenty-four\nbillions of dollars, but in 10 years\nthe republican party has decreased\ntit.-,: il, lit to about i-ixtrcii billion of\ndollar.-, l-htsland had a war debt of\nbillions, and still ha:-, it. Canada\nIs ju:.t as bad off. comparatively, jm\nlaiKland. After every war there is\nan inflation and then a deflation,\nand we are now in the midst of the\nexpected deflation. But we are on\nthe up grade. The republican party\nis getting ready to spend a billion\ndollars in government, state and\ntown and city projects that will give\nemployment to a great many unem\nployed men. Do not. turn over the\naffairs of the state and government\nto a group of persons who will ob\nstruct. this program.\nSays Gus Doesn't Enow\n\"My opponent, Gus Lonergan\ndoes not know what the protective\ntariff means, and I do not blame\nhim. He, sat with the democrats\nfrom the south, who. believe in free,\ntrade. xcent when it applies to\natory, demanded that republicans j g00(Js nlu,. n the south and Fold\nsent to Hartford so that ther.\nin be a bigger and better New\n'Britain through annexation of Kim\njf ill and Maple Hill sections of New\njjigton. Representative' Thuro Bengtson\nas chairman of the meeting, and\no had a different method of intro-\nuction for each speaker, which\n.rfiaughf the fancy of the audience.\nioivn, Committee Chairman- Harry\nlinsberg was the first speaker.\nf (I,-\n,4 tvUiji paring i im; .h:(ui ub ui hi,.- t j\nien heading the party tickets m\n'jfiie state, Krnest K.. Uogers and\nijlean Wilbur L. Cross, Mr. Gins\n:\"urg went to some length to de\nscribe the republican standard bear\n's public record.\n\"The democratic candidate Ins\n.ievcr siven even five minutes of his\ni4lme to the public, nor has be ha 1\ntiy experience at a.Il in political or\ngislaiivo work. He has been an\nfucator, and a ood one, probably'\nsaid.\nThe town chairman spoke warm\nof the three candidate:; from New\nritain to the general assembly, on\nto republican ticket. Senator Ki\ntl VV. Chri:.f. candidate for reele -Jion.\nand Representatives William\nSiange and Hengtson.\nJJ Seymour Extols New Britain\nCol. (.Clarence W. Seymour, can\n::date for congressman, was intro\nitfuced as \"one of the leading law.\nr of Connecticut, and a man who\nlis always commanded the respect\ni every person who has known\nI V\n-ol. SoymouF, who was to speak\nanother rally in Windsor last\nhere or abroad. Then they wanted\nprotection.\n\"James M. Cox, -who was al one\ntime candidate for the presidency\" on\nthe democratic ticket, in a speech\nmade two weeks ago. said that he\nhopes thai, the house and senate, w ill\nhe overwhelmingly democratic so\nthai the enlire tariff bill can be\nscrappvd. except the part that, ap\nplies to the agricultural intereata\n(he. was speaking before a group of\nfarmers).- Imagine the havoc in\nNew Britain if the tariff schedule is\nscrapped. Without protection your\nfactories will have to close down.\"\nRepresentative. William F. Lange\nmade a short plea for reelection on\nth grounds that lie knows what the\nworliinsiui-ii ir ed and outfit to have,\nand while lie did not have\" a college\neducation, he \"will study every bill\nand determine whether he ought to\nvote yes or no upon it before vot\ning.\" Believes Annexation Big Issue.\nMayor Quigley threw hot shot at\nthe camp of the enemy.\n\"One of the biggest things before\nthe legislature this next session, as\naffecting New Britain, will be the\nbill allowing this city to annex\nMaple Hill and Elm Hill, providing\nNewington will not object. Wc have\n8,800 acres of land in New Britain,\nand after taking out the parks,\nstreets, church and school grounds,\nledges and swamps, we have about\n4. oaii acres left upon which lo erect\nbuildings. By annexing those pa.rls 1\nof Newington we v.-ill add about 4.- j\n000 acres, and New llritain will have\na hance to grow. We will also\nthen have several miles of property\n'ht,drclarr,d .that h TvouM havej adjacent 4o the railroad lra:,u,,4\nbe ;brief, 1Ait \"ther Vro'ccrtain,) 4 vqus Lonergan goes rantinV \"and\nraving over this district, fitfrtiruT\nagainst the tariff hill. f v il 1 tell\nj nt for the resf of the republicans you why l.oner;an i:i so in! crerti.il\ni w the state to follow because of the in the removal of the tariff. Ituakob\nTightness of the prospects for a re- (you all know that fellow) is the\n!.piblican victory here next Tuesday. hi- man in the General Motors.\n;Je then explained at .length the I That, company plans to erect large\nyeaning of a protective tariff and buildings in Germany and inaaul'ac\nJJI1 the reason why he thought a I lure earn, and without a turijr'. bring\niJJ-publiean congress should be. elect- j ili.-tn over here and cell them at low\njof' I lirice::. thus throwing American la\nity \"In this day of a temporary de- lie:- out of employment. They don't\nstill mayor\nDenies G. O, I, to Blame\nHitting at the democratic thunder\nthat \"millions are out of work bo\ncause of the failure of the republi\ncans to keep prosperity going,\"\nMayor Carlson said that he read re\ncently that about twelve millions of\nmen and women are out of work in\nthe entire world.- \"Thiu proves;\" he\nlaid, \"that the condition is not\nlocal in your city here or in your\nstate or even in the United States.\nTherefore,' you cannot blame this\ncondition upon the republican party.\nThis slump is directly traceable to\nthe -world war. You cannot kill\nnearly 13;000, 000-persons and de\nstroy billions of dollars worth of\nproperty .without feeling the effects,\nand we are beginning to feel the\neffects.\n\"This is a machine, age, and\nproducta are catching up too fart\nfor conaumption. We are fortunate\nin having a man in Washington who\nbaa faced hg cmci-gencies. and he\nwill snide us (o a balance soon.\nWail street Interest\n\"The light against the tariff is of\ninterest to financiers. They want\nthe tariff off so that it will be pos\nsible to manufacture goods in Eu\nrope at lowr cost and dump them in\nAmerica. Many Wail Street men,\nsome of great prominence, oppose\nthe tariff because it keeps the cheap\ngoods out of this country. They ad\nvocate lower standards of living in\nthe United States for the working\nman, for they know that they can\nnot bring the wage standards in\nKurope up to the American level.\nThat, is way they are assisting the\ndemocratic parly. If there is a\ndemocratic house and senafc in\nWashington next, year it will mean\nthe wiping out of the tariff, and it\nwill also mean rule of this country\nby Tammany Hall. Judges are\nbought and sold in New York city.\nPay rolls arc padded. There is\ngraft and crookedness everywhere.\nThat is what this country will be if\ndemocrats are elected to the house\nand senate.\"\nWoods Speaks for Ailing\nProsecuting Attorney Joseph G.\nWoods was introduced as one of tin;\n\"old war horses of the republican\nparty in New Britain.\" After collud\ning the praises of the local republi\ncan candidates for the legislature.\nAttorney Woods spoke of Attorney\nBenjamin W. Ailing, against whom\nMr. Woods was opposed in a pri\nmary battle for the probate iudrrc-\nl.ihip a few weeks ago.\n\"Hen Allinsr- and T have been\nfriends for many years,\" he raid.\n\"We went to school together in\nKensington. We went to the New\nBritain high school togother. We.\nplayed football together and we\nwere in track meets together. After\nwe had finished' college, wo met\nagain and renewed that beautiful\nSerious Water Shortage\nThreatens at Newtown\nAeMW.vil, VVl. Ol (LX I a\nserfous water shortage faced resi\ndents of this community today.\nThe normal water supply has\nfailed and residents for miles\naround are obtaining water for\ndrinking, cooking and washing\nfrom an artesian well at the\nPalestine district school.\nThis summer's prolonged\ndrought is blamed for the shortage\nfriendship that we have for each\nother, and it has remained unbroken\nto this day.\n\"As prosecuting attorney. 1\nbrought -more than 10.000 cases\nbefore Judge Ailing when ho was\non the police, court bench, and in\nj every ease he was humane, kind\nj hearted and charitable, and that is\n'the kind of a man that you need\nI in the probate court. He is the. best\nman that it is possible to find in\nthis district for the job, and I urge,\nevery person in this hall to work\nhard for Ben Ailing.\"\nK. W. Christ on State Issues\nSenator K W. Chrst expressed\nsurprise that, there were any per\nsons left in the hall, because of the\nlateness of the hour and the length\nof the speeches, and admitted that\nhe was going to be very brief. He\nquoted figures on the number of pa\ntients in state sanatoria, state in\nsane hospitals and other state insti\ntutions, to allow- that the republican\nparty was taking good care of ill\nand needy persons, despite, the ac\ncusation that the \"democrats weic\nmaking at every rally about lack\nof humanitarian principles by the\nrepublican.-:.\"\n\"Is it not better to continue this\ngreat humanitarian work than to\nturn the state over to inexperienced\npersons simply because they advo\ncate a change?\" he said.\nMr. Christ reported that Mr.\nAiling was well on the road to re\ncovery, and tiie only reason that he\nwas not present at the rally was be\ncause his phyaicians had ordered\nhim to stay iti his home a few days\nlonger.\nhulAC Wakes 'Km I'p\n.Ttidje Anderson of Middletown\nawakened the audience, which had\nbecome somewhat drowsy from to\nmuch oratory, by his tremendous\nvoice and. sparkling vitality. Ho\nthundered against making any\nchanges and warned the members of\nthe John Ericsson club that the\nmembers must cast apathy aside and\nget into things along with the many\nother John Krlcsson clubs through\nout the country, for \"you cannot\nhave strength without militant co\noperation with all other clubs.\"\nReferring to Dean Cross, candi\ndate for governor on the democratic\nti\"!:et. Judge Anderson said, \"Our\ndear old friend, Dean Cross, is go\nins to have an old' ago pension, and\nhj is going to give away one hun\ndred million dollars, but he does\nnet tell you where ho is going to get\nthe money. Tile statu doe.i not have\nIt. The state has no money at all,\nKvcry cent that the state spends is\nyc r money, given by you in the\nform of taxe3, etc., and he is going\nto add plenty to that burden.. You\nwill pay the bill.\n\"Our roads are paid for. We have\nncl passed big bills on to our chil\ndren. In New York state they bond\ntheir road work and there, is one road\nnear Litchfield county that has been\nrebuilt three times, yet the bonds for\ntha first road are .-till there. Our\npa. -as-you-go policy is the beat one.\nam' the republican party of Connec\nticut will go forward along that\npolicy for many ycr.ro.\"\nCOM .lit .VIST HAU.V\nAt a communist rally held last\nnight at the Ukrainian hall at Er\nwin place a speaker told a gather\ning of about 100 persons that the\nworking nicn. now employed, will\nbe put on half time to give the un\nemployed an opportunity to earn a\nliving. This change will be brought\nabout by the unemployment com\nmission recently appointed by Pres\nident Hoover, it was said lo the\naudience.\nRobert Kling, the party candidate\nfor governor, attended. The audi\nence was urged to vote the com\nmunist ticket.\nUISHOI' CA.YNO.N BETTER\nWashington, Oct. 31 UP) Bishop\nJames Cannon, Jr., of the Methodist\nEpiscopal church, south, was \"more\nuncomfortable today\" as physicians\nsought unsuccessfully to halt the\nspread of arthritis which sent the\nchurchman to the hospital last week.\nDr. R. Lyman Sextion said al\nthough the bishop's temperature was\nslightly higher \"no alarm is felt for\nthe immediate future.\"\nron best KEsiTrs\nUSE HERALD CLASSI!'H: ADS\nFIRST AID COURSE\nCLASSWILL MEET\nGirl Scout Class to Goalinue\nBadge Winners Annouocel\n-The second class of the First Aid\neofirse which is conducted by Miss\nAgnes Fanning, in the Girl Scout\noffice on Saturday afternoons at -2\nwill be held this Saturday. Scouts\nare attending who are working on\nall tho stages of second, first and\nmerit badge first aid wprk. There\nis no charge for the course. Mis\nFanning having volunteered her\ntime and aerviees.\nIf the weather permits the Icad-ci-3\nof Girl Scout troops in New\nBritain and vicinity will have a\nparty at Camp Spraguc this Satur\nday. They will carry their 0W;i\nlunches and will go to camp as soon\nafter 4 o'clock as possible. They will\neat supper and entertain themselves\nin a manner suitable to Halloween.\nThe rain this afternoon spoiled\nthe plans of the New Britain scouts\nwho had planned to have a large\nbonfire and sing at Stanley Quarter\npark on the site of the Girl Scou\ncabin. The event was to have been\nin honor of Juliette Low's birthday,\nor Founder's Day. There would\nhave been a court or awards for all\nscouts who won badges at Camp\nSprague this summer. Thoae girls\nwho would have received badges\nare:\nTroop South Congregational\nTroop 1,. South Congregational\nbanks, second class; Anna Shimek.\nfirst class; Frances Crean, swimmer;\nRuth Raymond, pioneer; Carolyn\nLord, pioneer and cook; Mary Hor\nton, pioneer and cook; Eleanor Pot\nter, land animal, athlete, swimmer\nand woodcraft group badge; Anna\nShimek, wild flower, finder.\nTroop 1, Kensington: Angclinc.\nRio, scholarship; Frances Brown.\nEcholarship.\nTroop 2, First Congregational\nchurch, Katherino Boyle, observer;\nMarguerite Hulbert. cook.:\nTroop 3, First Baptist church:\nGladys Leavitt, pioneer.\nTroop 4, .BerliD: Nancy Hooker,\nwoodcraft, rambler, pioneer, wild\nflower finder, land animal: Betty\nUeining, athlete, child nurse; Mar\ngaret Flannery, observer.\n.Troop 5, Camp school: Gertrude\nLcubcck, observer.\nTroop S. Plalnville: Dorothy Sey\nmour, pioneer, cook; Florabelle\nParker, pioneer, cook; Maxine Bull,\nswimmer.\nTroop 10, Maple Hill: Lois How\nard, athlete, observer, land animal\nfinder, swimmer; Althea Iitham.\npioneer, cook; Constance Grant,\npioneer, cook; Betty Middlemass,\nswimmer.\nTroop 10. Stanley Memorial\nchurch: Gertrude Stone, pioneer,\ncook.\n'fhe ecurl of awards for the pres\nentation of these badges will be heii\nat the. Girl Scout office sonio after\nnoon. within the next two -weeks.\nNotice will be sent to those con\ncerned.\nThe lust two meetings In thu\ntraining course for leaders will Be\nheld ill the scout office next Tues\nday and Wednesday evenings. Miss\nRlehtcr will give instru-tlon in mak\ning stuffed toys Tuesday and on\nboth nights leaders will bo given a\nohance to pass tests and will receive\ninstruction in merit badge work in\nthe troop.\nSNOW I.N GOSHEN\"\nTorrington, Oct. 31 P) One inch\nof snow was reported in Goshen to\nday.\nFOR BEST RESULTS\nUSE HERALD CLASSIFIED ADS\nTHE PLAY SHOP\n500 MAIN STREET\nTELEPHONE 3423\nFor the convenience of those who wish to\nreserve their Christmas toys, and vehicles in\nadvance, we will be open evenings until 9 o'clock.\nCLARION RADIO\nIt Speaks for Itself\nI\nitha that yog ..should know;. He.\nnsidered New Uritaiitias a shining\nession it is wise to keep the high\nriff. wall because 90 per cent of\ne goods made in litis country is\nnsumed here, and we do not wan'.\nthis time in particular, foreign\njnjade (roods, made at very low costs\nl-pimped into this country and thus\njfcep the return of prosperity away\nJAy longer.\nJJ \"New 'Britain is affecled by In\nijistrial depression because of tho\nInvolution in Brazil and the high\ntariff on wheat in Italy. Italy to I\ntT wheat from Brazil, and now\njtiat Brar.il cannot ship because of\n;fe Internal state of affairs in that\nJiuntry, tho United Slates would he\nca about labor. They are interest-\ned in price selling competition that\nis favorable to them. i\n\"We have liecniies for peddlers j\nhere in New Britain. We have\nthem so that, our own peddlers can\nwork, and keep out.-:ide pcddlera\naway. All the tariff is. in a few\nwords. Is licenses that ket p outside\npcd'lh rs from Kurope away and allow-\nour own peddlers to .live.\"\nMayor Carlson of Jamestown,\nX. V.. was mayor ot that city for 20\nyeais. and expressing a desire to re\ntire three years ago. was out of\npolities for a year and then the city\ndratted him for mayor and he is\nTRUTH\nSTRANOKR\nTHAN FICTION\nSealing u3l3\ncontains no\nCricket Chirps;\nTell Temperature.;\nCricket Chirps are not nec\nessary to tell us that colt!\nweather is coming SOON.\nYou Had Better Let Us Install An\nA B.C. RANGE OIL BURNER\nBefore the Fir